article.headline: Gipson scores season-high as K-State topples No. 13 Oklahoma St.
article.story:
STILLWATER, Okla. (AP) -- Entering conference play, Kansas State coach Deb Patterson said the primary difference between the Wildcats and Top 25 teams from the Big 12 Conference was "a couple of losses."

That difference has pretty much been erased during the past three weeks as the Wildcats (No. 22 AP) have zoomed to the top of the Big 12. Their 68-63 win on Sunday afternoon over Oklahoma State (No. 13 ESPN/USA Today, No. 14 AP) was their fourth in a row against a ranked team since league play started.

Kansas State (14-5, 6-0) has won nine straight games after a 5-5 start and is tied with Baylor atop the Big 12, having already recorded road wins over South Division foes Texas A&M, Texas and Oklahoma State. Kansas State and Baylor are two games ahead of their nearest rivals.

Kansas State's 6-0 start is its best since the Big 12 came into existence with the 1996-97 season. The Wildcats started 8-0 in league play on three occasions as members of the Big Eight Conference.

The Wildcats took their lumps during nonconference play, losing road games at places like Wyoming, Creighton and Wisconsin-Green Bay, but Patterson and her players say those experiences have proven invaluable with the arrival of Big 12 games.

"We saw a lot of different teams and a lot of different styles and that allowed us to work on our weaknesses," said junior guard Shalee Lehning, who had 13 points and six assists. "It helped us build the character we needed. It helped us come together as a unit and be five players out there."

The contributions came from all over the basketball court against Oklahoma State. Marlies Gipson had season highs with 21 points and 16 rebounds and Kimberly Dietz overcame early struggles to hit four 3-pointers in the second half to help the Wildcats rally, then pull ahead of Oklahoma State (16-3, 4-2).

"It sounds simplistic, but it's so impressive to see a player struggle in the first half then come back and dominate in the second half," Patterson said of Dietz.

Oklahoma State lost its second straight game, having also fallen to Texas on Wednesday. Point guard Andrea Riley led the Cowgirls with 34 points (on 12 of 34 shooting) and added nine rebounds, but that wasn't enough to preserve the Cowgirls' 12-game winning streak at Gallagher-Iba Arena.

"Going on the road is always something that is really hard in the Big 12," Dietz said. "I think we've stepped up to the plate and done really well ... It's all about being confident when you go to these places and playing the game and not letting anything rattle you."

Oklahoma State entered the game atop the Big 12 in scoring offense, averaging 80.3 points per game, but scored fewer than 70 for the third straight contest. Kansas State entered the game third in the Big 12 in scoring defense, allowing an average of 55.7 points per game.

"You can't make mistakes and beat a team like Kansas State, because they don't beat themselves," Oklahoma State coach Kurt Budke said. "We can't have one person in double figures and win a game like this."

Kansas State didn't trail during the final 13 minutes, but the Wildcats never could pull away from Oklahoma State. Twice in the final minutes, Oklahoma State cut the Wildcats' lead to three points. The first time, Dietz answered with a 3-pointer to make it 64-58 with 1:20 left.

Then, after Riley brought the Cowgirls within 66-63 on a 3-pointer with 11.6 seconds left, Dietz made 1 of 2 free throws with 8.9 seconds left to seal the win for the Wildcats. She finished with 20 points, two off her season high.

Gipson, who also had five blocked shots, three steals and three assists, added 1 of 2 free throws with under a second left. Kansas State won despite being outrebounded 52-30.

The lead swapped hands 10 times in the first half, with the Cowgirls scoring the final five points to take a 32-28 lead -- their largest of the game to that point. Oklahoma State missed its first seven shots of the second half, but four Kansas State turnovers allowed the Cowgirls to maintain, then extend, their lead to 37-30 with 15:36 left on a basket by Maria Cordero.

Then Dietz, who missed her first four 3-point attempts, hit two in a row -- the second from 25 feet -- to energize the Wildcats and start a 15-2 run.

Dietz hit another 3-pointer and Lehning added six points during the run, including a reverse lay-in following a baseline drive with 11:30 left that put Kansas State up 45-39.
